Truthiness — what counts as false.

Every python object can be used in a boolean context — if x, while x, bool of x. The default rule. An object is truthy unless it is one of these — false, none, numeric zero, an empty container, an empty bytes or bytearray, or any object whose dunder bool returns false, or whose dunder len returns zero.

This rule is the basis of python's most idiomatic is there anything here check. If items, do something — not if l-e-n of items greater than zero. The same trick fires for strings, dicts, and so on. It is the python equivalent of is it set, and not empty, in one line.

In code, picture a loop over a list of values — false, none, zero, zero point zero, empty string, empty list, empty dict, empty tuple, empty set, empty bytes — and the truthy counterparts. For each, print the value and what bool returns. You see all the empties resolve to false; all the populated values resolve to true.
